			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64138370"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64138370"><p><span class="substr"> </span> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Langdon_Winner" title="wikipedia.org">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...</a> [wikipedia.org] <br>"In 1980 Winner proposed that technologies embody social relations, i.e. power.[2] To the question he poses "Do Artifacts Have Politics?", Winner identifies two ways in which artifacts can have politics. The first, involving technical arrangements and social order, concerns how the invention, design, or arrangement of artifacts or the larger system becomes a mechanism for settling the affairs of a community. This way "transcends the simple categories of 'intended' and 'unint</p></div>
	</div>

